---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Aside from '../../../components/Aside.astro';
import {cacheSidebar} from '../../../data/cache-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Background Refresh" sidebar={cacheSidebar}
            description="Stale-while-revalidate: serve old values while refreshing in the background">

    <h1>Background Refresh</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Stale-while-revalidate for your cache. When an entry gets old, refresh it in the background —
        no reader ever sees a miss, no reader ever waits.
    </p>

    <h2>The problem with expiry</h2>

    <p>With <code>expireAfterWrite</code>, when the TTL passes the entry is gone. The next reader pays the full cost
        of reloading it — a database query, an API call, whatever. Under high traffic, many readers can hit that gap
        simultaneously.</p>

    <p><code>refreshAfterWrite</code> flips this: when the TTL passes, the <strong>stale value keeps being
        served</strong>
        while a background coroutine quietly reloads it. No reader ever sees a miss.</p>

    <Aside>This is the stale-while-revalidate pattern from HTTP caching, applied to an in-memory cache.
        If you've used Caffeine's <code>refreshAfterWrite</code>, it's the same idea.
    </Aside>

    <h2>Basic usage</h2>

    <Code code={`import io.peekandpoke.ultra.cache.fastCache
import kotlin.time.Duration.Companion.minutes

val cache = fastCache<String, UserProfile> {
    refreshAfterWrite(ttl = 5.minutes) { key ->
        // This is a suspend function — runs in a background coroutine
        userService.fetchProfile(key)
    }
}

// First put — starts the TTL clock
cache.put("user:42", initialProfile)

// After 5 minutes:
// - Reader A gets the old profile instantly (no wait)
// - A background coroutine calls userService.fetchProfile("user:42")
// - Reader B (moments later) gets the new profile`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>The loader function receives the key and returns the new value. It runs in the cache's
        <code>CoroutineScope</code>, so it integrates with structured concurrency.</p>

    <h2>Hard TTL</h2>

    <p>What if the loader is slow or keeps failing? You might not want to serve infinitely stale data.
        The optional <code>hardTtl</code> parameter evicts entries past a hard deadline, even during a refresh:</p>

    <Code code={`val cache = fastCache<String, String> {
    refreshAfterWrite(
        ttl = 5.minutes,          // start refreshing after 5 minutes
        hardTtl = 30.minutes,     // evict completely after 30 minutes
    ) { key ->
        fetchFromApi(key)
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Without <code>hardTtl</code>, stale entries are served indefinitely as long as a refresh is in-flight or
        pending. With it, you get a backstop.</p>

    <h2>Deduplication</h2>

    <p>Only one refresh runs per key at a time. If the cache detects that key <code>"x"</code> is stale and a
        refresh is already in-flight, it skips launching another one. When the refresh completes and calls
        <code>cache.put()</code>, the write timestamp resets and the entry is fresh again.</p>

    <h2>Error handling</h2>

    <p>If the loader throws, the refresh is considered failed. The key is marked as eligible for retry on the
        next processing loop iteration (~50ms later). This means a transient failure (network blip, temporary
        API error) will self-heal on the next loop cycle.</p>

    <Code code={`var attempt = 0

val cache = fastCache<String, String> {
    refreshAfterWrite(ttl = 5.minutes) { key ->
        attempt++
        if (attempt == 1) error("transient failure")
        fetchFromApi(key)  // succeeds on retry
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <Aside>There is no built-in exponential backoff. If you need it, implement it in your loader function.
        The cache just retries on every loop iteration until the loader succeeds or the hard TTL evicts the entry.
    </Aside>

    <h2>Combining with other behaviours</h2>

    <p>Stack <code>refreshAfterWrite</code> with other behaviours for fine-grained control:</p>

    <Code code={`val cache = fastCache<String, UserProfile> {
    refreshAfterWrite(ttl = 5.minutes) { key ->
        userService.fetchProfile(key)
    }
    maxEntries(10_000)               // hard cap on entry count
    onEviction { key, _ ->            // log evictions
        logger.info("evicted ${'$'}key")
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Note: <code>refreshAfterWrite</code> and <code>expireAfterWrite</code> are independent behaviours.
        If you use both, the write-TTL eviction happens regardless of whether a refresh is pending. Use
        <code>hardTtl</code> on the refresh behaviour instead if you want the refresh to have a deadline.</p>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/cache/observability"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Observability &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
